using namespace std;
int main()
{
    const int MIN_NUMBER = 0,
              NUM_OF_STORES = 5,
              HUNDRED = 100;

    int store_1,
        store_2,
        store_3,
        store_4,
        store_5,
        store_1_100s, 
        store_2_100s, 
        store_3_100s, 
        store_4_100s, 
        store_5_100s;

    cout << "\nEnter today's sales for store 1: ";
    cin >> store_1;
    store_1_100s = store_1 / HUNDRED; // 200/100 = 2

    cout << "Enter today's sales for store 2: ";
    cin >> store_2;
    store_2_100s = store_2 / HUNDRED; // 300/100 = 3

    cout << "Enter today's sales for store 3: ";
    cin >> store_3;
    store_3_100s = store_3 / HUNDRED;

    cout << "Enter today's sales for store 4: ";
    cin >> store_4;
    store_4_100s = store_4 / HUNDRED;
    
    cout << "Enter today's sales for store 5: ";
    cin >> store_5;
    store_5_100s = store_5 / HUNDRED;

    cout << "\nSALES BAR CHART" << endl;
    cout << "(Each * = $100)" << endl;
    cout << "Store 1: ";
    for (int i = MIN_NUMBER; i < store_1_100s; i++)
        cout << '*';

    cout << endl;

    cout << "Store 2: ";
    for (int i = MIN_NUMBER; i < store_2_100s; i++)
        cout << '*';

    cout << endl;

    cout << "Store 3: ";
    for (int i = MIN_NUMBER; i < store_3_100s; i++)
        cout << '*'; 

    cout << endl;

    cout << "Store 4: ";
    for (int i = MIN_NUMBER; i < store_4_100s; i++)
        cout << '*';

    cout << endl;
    
    cout << "Store 5: ";
    for (int i = MIN_NUMBER; i < store_5_100s; i++)
        cout << '*';
        
    cout << '\n' << endl;

    return 0;
}

18/12/2020, 10:11â€¯am - Syed Abdul Hanan: #include <iostream>
#include <ctime>

using namespace std;

int main()
{
char choice;

cout << "Welcome to the coin flip game. It costs a dollar to play." << endl;
cout << "If you guess correctly, you will win $2.00" << endl;
cout << "If you guess correctly, you will match your bet one to one." << endl;
cout << "Do you want to play (Y/N)? ";
cin >> choice;

char computer_choice[] {'H', 'T'};

srand (time_t(NULL));

char guess;
int num = rand() % 2;

double bank = 14.00;
int winnings = 0.0;

while (toupper(choice) == 'Y')
{
cout << "Your bank balance is $" << bank << endl;

cout << "Enter heads or tails (H/T) ";
cin >> guess;
guess = toupper(guess);
num = rand() % 2;

char computer_throw = computer_choice[num];
cout << "Computer throws " << computer_throw << '\n';

if (guess == computer_throw)
{
cout << "You win\n";
winnings = 2.00;
}
else
{
cout << "You lost\n";
winnings = -2.00;
}

num = rand() % 2;

bank += winnings;
}

return 0;
}

The biggest data breach in the history of Pakistan took place within the governmentâ€™s own organization NADRA in 2018. In 2011 PITB (Pakistan Information Technology board) digitized the decades old sensitive government data like police records, Land records and such. It was a great achievement but without thinking about its implications, PTIB started to make this confidential data public along with the bio data of 200 million Pakistani citizens acquired from NADRA through various APIâ€™s. Mobile apps and web portals without any proper cybersecurity control were made for govt. officials having direct access to Nadra, Teleco and PTIB data. There apps and credentials to the portals got leaked over time and now they were being sold online for 200 rupees per copy. The information about Pakistani citizens sold online included names, addresses, driving licenses associated with CNIC numbers, criminal records, call details, location, whether or not someone has taken a loan and so on. The data was sold in private groups on Facebook and Whatsapp as well as directly by those who have or had access to the system. In one case, call records of any cell phone number were being sold for 100 rupees only. It was an alarming situation for the entire nation. All of their private data was leaked and in the hands of criminals. This was a huge insult to all law abiding citizens of the country. 07/02/2021, 1:34â€¯am - Shafi: Missed voice call
07/02/2021, 1:38â€¯am - Shafi: Yes sir, I have used recursive function in Question 2. 
The user enters positive integer number and the number is passed to the Factorial function.
Suppose the number 5 is passed to the Factorial function then 5 is multiplied to the Factorial of (5-1) = 4. Then 4 is passed to the Factorial function again .
Then 4 is multiplied to the Factorial function (4-1) = 3. and 3 is again passed to the function.
This procedure is repeated until the number reaches the value 1 and the function returns 1.
Sir, the Factorial function calls itself again and again until the value of number reaches 1. That is because I have put the IF condition (n > 1) .
If the user enters the number which is less than 1, then the Factorial function will return 1. That is because of the ELSE condition within the function definition.

22/05/2021, 11:28â€¯am - Shafi: //Name: Shafi Ur Rehman
//Roll Number: 203084

#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

class Players
{
	private:
		int index;
		string *full_name;
		int *age;
		int *scoring_average;
		string *gender;
		string *feild_position;
		int *players;

		public:
			Players(int size)
			{
				index = size;
				players = new int[size];
				full_name = new string[size];
				age = new int[size];
				scoring_average = new int[size];
				gender = new string[size];
				feild_position = new string[size];
			}
			
			void setindex(int s)
			{
				index = s;
			}
			int getindex()
			{
				return index;
			}
			
			void setfullname(int index, string n)
			{
				full_name[index] = n;
			}
			string getfullname(int index)
			{
				return full_name[index];
			}
			
			void set_age(int index, int a)
			{
				age[index] = a;
			}
			int get_age(int index)
			{
				return age[index];
			}
			
			void set_scoring_avg(int index, int s)
			{
				scoring_average[index] = s;
			}
			int get_scoring_avg(int index)
			{
				return scoring_average[index];
			}
			
			void set_gender(int index, string g)
			{
				gender[index] = g;
			}
			string get_gender(int index)
			{
				return gender[index];
			}
			
			void set_feild_position(int index, string f)
			{
				feild_position[index] = f;
			}
			string get_feild_position(int index)
			{
				return feild_position[index];
			}
			
			friend istream &operator>>( istream  &input, Players &D ) 
			{ 
      		   // Player temp[index];
				for(int i=0; i<D.index; i++)
				{
					cout<<"\nPlayer # "<<i+1<<endl;
					cout<<"Enter Full Name: ";
					cin.ignore();
					getline(input,D.full_name[i]);
					cout<<"ENter age: ";
					input>>D.age[i];
					cout<<"Enter Scoring Average: ";
					input>>D.scoring_average[i];
					cout<<"Enter Gender: ";
					cin.ignore();
					getline(input,D.gender[i]);
					cout<<"Enter feild position: ";
					getline(input,D.feild_position[i]);
				}
        		return input;            
      		}
      		
      		friend ostream &operator<<( ostream  &output, const Players &D ) 
			{ 
      		   // Player temp[index];
				for(int i=0; i<D.index; i++)
				{
					output<<"\nPlayer # "<<i+1<<endl;
					output<<"Enter Full Name: "<<D.full_name[i]<<endl;
					output<<"ENter age: "<<D.age[i]<<endl;
					output<<"Enter Scoring Average: "<<D.scoring_average[i]<<endl;
					output<<"Enter Gender: "<<D.gender[i]<<endl;
					output<<"Enter feild position: "<<D.feild_position[i]<<endl<<endl;
				}
        		return output;            
      		}
      		
      		void highest_scoring_player()
      		{
      			  for(int i = 1;i < index; ++i)
  					{
   					    // Change < to > if you want to find the smallest element
   					    if(scoring_average[0] < scoring_average[i])
   				        scoring_average[0] = scoring_average[i];
  			 		}	
  			 	cout<<"\nPlayer with Highest Scoring Average: "<<endl;
					cout<<"Full Name: "<<full_name[0]<<endl;
					cout<<"Age: "<<age[0]<<endl;
					cout<<"Scoring Average: "<<scoring_average[0]<<endl;
					cout<<"Gender: "<<gender[0]<<endl;
					cout<<"Feild position: "<<feild_position[0]<<endl<<endl;
			}
	
      		void lowest_scoring_player()
      		{
      			  for(int i = 1;i < index; ++i)
  					{
   					    // Change < to > if you want to find the smallest element
   					    if(scoring_average[0] > scoring_average[i])
   				        scoring_average[0] = scoring_average[i];
  			 		}	
  			 	cout<<"\nPlayer with Lowest Scoring Average: "<<endl;
					cout<<"Full Name: "<<full_name[0]<<endl;
					cout<<"Age: "<<age[0]<<endl;
					cout<<"Scoring Average: "<<scoring_average[0]<<endl;
					cout<<"Gender: "<<gender[0]<<endl;
					cout<<"Feild position: "<<feild_position[0]<<endl<<endl;
			}
			
			friend void SearchMyPlayer(Players);
			
			~Players()
			{
				full_name = 0;
				age = 0;
				scoring_average = 0;
				gender = 0;
				feild_position = 0;
				players = 0;
			}
			
			void displaydata(int i)
			{
					cout<<"Enter Full Name: "<<full_name[i]<<endl;
					cout<<"ENter age: "<<age[i]<<endl;
					cout<<"Enter Scoring Average: "<<scoring_average[i]<<endl;
					cout<<"Enter Gender: "<<gender[i]<<endl;
					cout<<"Enter feild position: "<<feild_position[i]<<endl<<endl;
			}
};

void SearchMyPlayer(Players P)
{
	string search;
	cout<<"Enter players name you want to search: ";
	getline(cin,search);
	int index;
	    for(int i =0; i< P.getindex(); i++){
        if(search == P.getfullname(i))
		{
            index = i;
        }
        P.displaydata(index);

}
}

int main()
{
	int size;
	cout<<"Enter the number of players: ";
	cin>>size;
	
	Players obj(size);
	cin >> obj;
	cout<< obj;
	obj.highest_scoring_player();
	obj.lowest_scoring_player();
	
	
	SearchMyPlayer(obj);
	return 0;	
}

26/05/2021, 12:02â€¯pm - Shafi: Discuss the main features of Islamic Economic System.
26/05/2021, 12:30â€¯pm - Shafi: Kinds of Hadees:
There Are three types of Hadith-e-Qauli, Faili and
Taqreeri.
1-Hadees Qauli: ( ïº£ïºªï»³ïºš ï»—ï»®ï»Ÿï»° )
Hadith-e-Qauli is the kind of Hadees in which the
sayings of the prophet (sallallahu alaihi wasallam)
are mentioned.
2-Hadith-e-Faili:( ïº£ïºªï»³ïºš ï»“ï»Œï» ï»° )
Hadith-e-Faili is that kind of Hadees in which the
deeds and lifestyle of the holy prophet (sallallahu
alaihi wasallam) is mentioned.
3-Hadees Taqreeri:( ïº£ïºªï»³ïºš ïº—ï»˜ïº®ï»³ïº®ï»¯ )
Hadees Taqreeri is the kind of Hadees in which the
silence of the holy Prophet (sallallahu alaihi
wasallam) is mentioned when his companion did
some thing or said some thing in his presence.

Yes  caring about the your deeds should be first priority and who ever doesn't do that is on  wrong path. But that doesn't mean he/she will be wrong forever. No one is born with the sense of good and bad ..every human and every event has some worth in it ; maybe a lesson for you learn something from it, maybe a opportunity to do good, maybe a human to change your perspective, maybe Allah want you to  be happy and thank him for it, maybe Allah wants you to be sad and get close to him. This post I know gives a slight sense of realising what's important .... but it is somewhere  giving more vibes of  leaving this world completely which is opposite of what is written in every scripture of it and giving a vibe that Allah is less merciful which is totally absurd. Had he wanted that only he wouldn't send us to this world. One should always believe in his mercy more than his wrath. He even gives to those who don't obey him in this world. So the focus should be to fulfill the obligatory commands like salah, zakat etc and even fulfilling these makes you realise that it gives your soul a positive energy. 23/11/2022, 7:50â€¯pm - Shafi: Massive economic gains over the past fifty years have been largely a result of multilateralism. The multilateral economic system's accomplishments are becoming more and more undervalued as it becomes more and more accepted, yet as globalisation advances, there is a greater need than ever for a multilateral international economic system. I'll make the case that over the past sixty years, the international financial institutions have done a remarkable job of supporting economic prosperity of previously unheard-of dimensions. 12/12/2022, 2:41â€¯pm - Syed Abdul Hanan: using System;
using System.Collections.Generic;

namespace ShopManagement
{
    class Shop
    {
        // Create a list to store the items in the shop's inventory
        List<Item> inventory = new List<Item>();

        // Method to add an item to the inventory
        public void AddItem(string name, double price)
        {
            inventory.Add(new Item(name, price));
        }

        // Method to remove an item from the inventory
        public void RemoveItem(string name)
        {
            // Find the item with the specified name in the inventory
            Item item = inventory.Find(x => x.Name == name);

            // If the item is found, remove it from the inventory
            if (item != null)
            {
                inventory.Remove(item);
            }
        }

        // Method to calculate the total value of the inventory
        public double CalculateInventoryValue()
        {
            double total = 0;

            // Loop through the inventory and add the price of each item to the total
            foreach (Item item in inventory)
            {
                total += item.Price;
            }

            return total;
        }

        // Method to display the inventory
        public void DisplayInventory()
        {
            // Loop through the inventory and print the name and price of each item
            foreach (Item item in inventory)
            {
                Console.WriteLine($"{item.Name}: ${item.Price}");
            }
        }
    }

    // Class to represent an item in the shop's inventory
    class Item
    {
        // Properties of the Item class
        public string Name { get; set; }
        public double Price { get; set; }

        // Constructor to create a new Item object
        public Item(string name, double price)
        {
            this.Name = name;
            this.Price = price;
        }
    }
}
12/12/2022, 2:42â€¯pm - Syed Abdul Hanan: This code creates a Shop class that has methods for adding and removing items from the inventory, calculating the total value of the inventory, and displaying the inventory. The Item class is used to represent an individual item in the shop's inventory, with properties for the item's name and price.

12/12/2022, 2:45â€¯pm - Syed Abdul Hanan: using System;
using System.Collections.Generic;

namespace ShopManagement
{
    class Shop
    {
        // Create a list to store the items in the shop's inventory
        List<Item> inventory = new List<Item>();

        // Create a ledger for recording transactions
        Ledger ledger = new Ledger();

        // Method to add an item to the inventory
        public void AddItem(string name, double price)
        {
            inventory.Add(new Item(name, price));
        }

        // Method to remove an item from the inventory
        public void RemoveItem(string name)
        {
            // Find the item with the specified name in the inventory
            Item item = inventory.Find(x => x.Name == name);

            // If the item is found, remove it from the inventory
            if (item != null)
            {
                inventory.Remove(item);
            }
        }

        // Method to record a sale in the ledger
        public void RecordSale(string itemName, int quantity, double price)
        {
            ledger.RecordSale(itemName, quantity, price);
        }

        // Method to calculate the total value of the inventory
        public double CalculateInventoryValue()
        {
            double total = 0;

            // Loop through the inventory and add the price of each item to the total
            foreach (Item item in inventory)
            {
                total += item.Price;
            }

            return total;
        }

        // Method to display the inventory
        public void DisplayInventory()
        {
            // Loop through the inventory and print the name and price of each item
            foreach (Item item in inventory)
            {
                Console.WriteLine($"{item.Name}: ${item.Price}");
            }
        }

        // Method to display the ledger
        public void DisplayLedger()
        {
            ledger.Display();
        }
    }

    // Class to represent an item in the shop's inventory
    class Item
    {
        // Properties of the Item class
        public string Name { get; set; }
        public double Price { get; set; }

        // Constructor to create a new Item object
        public

03/01/2023, 1:48â€¯am - Shafi: It is often difficult to change someone's mind, especially if the person is overconfident, stubborn, narcissistic, or disagreeable. However, with the right approach, it is possible to persuade people to reevaluate their positions and consider alternative perspectives. One approach is to ask a know-it-all to explain how things work. This can help to reveal gaps in their understanding and humility, as it can be a humbling experience to try to explain something complex. Another approach is to let a stubborn person seize the reins and shape their own ideas, rather than trying to force them to accept yours. This can be done by asking questions and planting seeds of new concepts, rather than giving answers or presenting fully formed ideas. When dealing with a narcissist, it is important to praise them in areas different from the one in which you hope to change their mind, and to appeal to their desire for admiration and approval. This can counteract their insecurity and their tendency to reject a difference of opinion as criticism. To persuade a disagreeable person, it may be helpful to engage in a respectful and constructive debate, and to stand up to them rather than backing down. By using these approaches and being open to other perspectives, it is possible to persuade people to change their minds. It is also important for organizations to have strong and visionary leaders, but it is also important for them to have employees and stakeholders who are willing to challenge and question those leaders in a respectful and constructive way. This can help to foster greater cognitive flexibility and the ability to adapt to changing circumstances. One example of a leader who initially struggled to be open to other perspectives and to change his own convictions is Steve Jobs. However, he eventually learned
03/01/2023, 1:48â€¯am - Shafi: that it was necessary to surround himself with people who knew how to challenge him and help him overcome his own worst instincts. This ultimately contributed to Apple's success. In summary, to effectively persuade others to change their minds, it is important to understand and address their specific barriers to persuasion, whether it be overconfidence, stubbornness, narcissism, or disagreeableness. By approaching the situation with tact and respect, and being open to alternative perspectives, it is possible to persuade others to consider new ideas and reevaluate their positions.
03/01/2023, 1:48â€¯am - Shafi: To persuade a know-it-all to recognize when there's something to be learned, it can be helpful to ask them to explain how things work. This can be a humbling experience and may allow them to recognize the gaps in their own understanding. To encourage a stubborn person to make a change, it can be helpful to let them seize the reins and take control of the conversation. By asking questions and inviting them to share their thoughts, you can give them a sense of ownership over the process. When trying to persuade a narcissistic person, it is important to praise them in an area different from the one in which you hope to change their mind. This can make them more open to acknowledging their flaws and imperfections. When dealing with a disagreeable person, it can be helpful to stand up to them and be willing to argue and fight for your ideas. By persistently refining and repeating your pitch, acknowledging and addressing weaknesses, offering proof of concept, and enlisting supporters, you can eventually persuade them to consider your perspective. In general, it is important to approach persuasion with respect and openness, and to be willing to listen to and consider alternative viewpoints.

18/01/2023, 8:21â€¯pm - Syed Abdul Hanan: # Python program for Dijkstra's single
# source shortest path algorithm. The program is
# for adjacency matrix representation of the graph
class Graph():
 
    def __init__(self, vertices):
18/01/2023, 8:21â€¯pm - Syed Abdul Hanan: self.V = vertices
        self.graph = [[0 for column in range(vertices)]
                      for row in range(vertices)]
 
    def printSolution(self, dist):
        print("Vertex \t Distance from Source")
        for node in range(self.V):
            print(node, "\t\t", dist[node])
 
    # A utility function to find the vertex with
    # minimum distance value, from the set of vertices
    # not yet included in shortest path tree
    def minDistance(self, dist, sptSet):
 
        # Initialize minimum distance for next node
        min = 1e7
 
        # Search not nearest vertex not in the
        # shortest path tree
        for v in range(self.V):
            if dist[v] < min and sptSet[v] == False:
                min = dist[v]
                min_index = v
 
        return min_index
 
    # Function that implements Dijkstra's single source
    # shortest path algorithm for a graph represented
    # using adjacency matrix representation
    def dijkstra(self, src):
 
        dist = [1e7] * self.V
        dist[src] = 0
        sptSet = [False] * self.V
 
        for cout in range(self.V):
 
            # Pick the minimum distance vertex from
            # the set of vertices not yet processed.
            # u is always equal to src in first iteration
            u = self.minDistance(dist, sptSet)
 
            # Put the minimum distance vertex in the
            # shortest path tree
            sptSet[u] = True
 
            # Update dist value of the adjacent vertices
            # of the picked vertex only if the current
            # distance is greater than new distance and
            # the vertex in not in the shortest path tree
            for v in range(self.V):
                if (self.graph[u][v] > 0 and
                   sptSet[v] == False and
                   dist[v] > dist[u] + self.graph[u][v]):
                    dist[v] = dist[u] + self.graph[u][v]
 
        self.printSolution(dist)
 
# Driver program
g = Graph(9)
g.graph = [[0, 4, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 8, 0],
           [4, 0, 8, 0, 0, 0, 0, 11, 0],
           [0, 8, 0, 7, 0, 4, 0, 0, 2],
           [0, 0, 7, 0, 9, 14, 0, 0, 0],
           [0, 0, 0, 9, 0, 10, 0, 0, 0],
           [0, 0, 4, 14, 10, 0, 2, 0, 0],
           [0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 2, 0, 1, 6],
           [8, 11, 0, 0, 0, 0, 1, 0, 7],
           [0, 0, 2, 0, 0, 0, 6, 7, 0]
           ]
 
g.dijkstra(0)

18/01/2023, 8:24â€¯pm - Syed Abdul Hanan: // Dijkstra's Algorithm in C++

#include <iostream>
#include <vector>

#define INT_MAX 10000000

using namespace std;

void DijkstrasTest();

int main() {
  DijkstrasTest();
  return 0;
}

class Node;
class Edge;

void Dijkstras();
vector<Node*>* AdjacentRemainingNodes(Node* node);
Node* ExtractSmallest(vector<Node*>& nodes);
int Distance(Node* node1, Node* node2);
bool Contains(vector<Node*>& nodes, Node* node);
void PrintShortestRouteTo(Node* destination);

vector<Node*> nodes;
vector<Edge*> edges;

class Node {
   public:
  Node(char id)
    : id(id), previous(NULL), distanceFromStart(INT_MAX) {
    nodes.push_back(this);
  }

   public:
  char id;
  Node* previous;
  int distanceFromStart;
};

class Edge {
   public:
  Edge(Node* node1, Node* node2, int distance)
    : node1(node1), node2(node2), distance(distance) {
    edges.push_back(this);
  }
  bool Connects(Node* node1, Node* node2) {
    return (
      (node1 == this->node1 &&
       node2 == this->node2) ||
      (node1 == this->node2 &&
       node2 == this->node1));
  }

   public:
  Node* node1;
  Node* node2;
  int distance;
};

///////////////////
void DijkstrasTest() {
  Node* a = new Node('a');
  Node* b = new Node('b');
  Node* c = new Node('c');
  Node* d = new Node('d');
  Node* e = new Node('e');
  Node* f = new Node('f');
  Node* g = new Node('g');

  Edge* e1 = new Edge(a, c, 1);
  Edge* e2 = new Edge(a, d, 2);
  Edge* e3 = new Edge(b, c, 2);
  Edge* e4 = new Edge(c, d, 1);
  Edge* e5 = new Edge(b, f, 3);
  Edge* e6 = new Edge(c, e, 3);
  Edge* e7 = new Edge(e, f, 2);
  Edge* e8 = new Edge(d, g, 1);
  Edge* e9 = new Edge(g, f, 1);

  a->distanceFromStart = 0;  // set start node
  Dijkstras();
  PrintShortestRouteTo(f);
}

///////////////////

void Dijkstras() {
  while (nodes.size() > 0) {
    Node* smallest = ExtractSmallest(nodes);
    vector<Node*>* adjacentNodes =
      AdjacentRemainingNodes(smallest);

    const int size = adjacentNodes->size();
    for (int i = 0; i < size; ++i) {
      Node* adjacent = adjacentNodes->at(i);
      int distance = Distance(smallest, adjacent) +
               smallest->distanceFromStart;

      if (distance < adjacent->distanceFromStart) {
        adjacent->distanceFromStart = distance;
        adjacent->previous = smallest;
      }
    }
    delete adjacentNodes;
  }
}

// Find the node with the smallest distance,
// remove it, and return it.
Node* ExtractSmallest(vector<Node*>& nodes) {
  int size = nodes.size();
  if (size == 0) return NULL;
  int smallestPosition = 0;
  Node* smallest = nodes.at(0);
  for (int i = 1; i < size; ++i) {
    Node* current = nodes.at(i);
    if (current->distanceFromStart <
      smallest->distanceFromStart) {
      smallest = current;
      smallestPosition = i;
    }
  }
  nodes.erase(nodes.begin() + smallestPosition);
  return smallest;
}

// Return all nodes adjacent to 'node' which are still
// in the 'nodes' collection.
vector<Node*>* AdjacentRemainingNodes(Node* node) {
  vector<Node*>* adjacentNodes = new vector<Node*>();
  const int size = edges.size();
  for (int i = 0; i < size; ++i) {
    Edge* edge = edges.at(i);
    Node* adjacent = NULL;
    if (edge->node1 == node) {
      adjacent = edge->node2;
    } else if (edge->node2 == node) {
      adjacent = edge->node1;
    }
    if (adjacent && Contains(nodes, adjacent)) {
      adjacentNodes->push_back(adjacent);
    }
  }
  return adjacentNodes;
}

// Return distance between two connected nodes
int Distance(Node* node1, Node* node2) {
  const int size = edges.size();
  for (int i = 0; i < size; ++i) {
    Edge* edge = edges.at(i);
    if (edge->Connects(node1, node2)) {
      return edge->distance;
    }
  }
  return -1;  // should never happen
}

// Does the 'nodes' vector contain 'node'
bool Contains(vector<Node*>& nodes, Node* node) {
  const int size = nodes.size();
  for (int i = 0; i < size; ++i) {
    if (node == nodes.at(i)) {
      return true;
    }
  }
  return false;
}

///////////////////

void PrintShortestRouteTo(Node* destination) {
  Node* previous = destination;
  cout << "Distance from start: "
     << destination->distanceFromStart << endl;
  while (previous) {
    cout << previous->id << " ";
    previous = previous->previous;
  }
  cout << endl;
}

// these two not needed
vector<Edge*>* AdjacentEdges(vector<Edge*>& Edges, Node* node);
void RemoveEdge(vector<Edge*>& Edges, Edge* edge);

vector<Edge*>* AdjacentEdges(vector<Edge*>& edges, Node* node) {
  vector<Edge*>* adjacentEdges = new vector<Edge*>();

  const int size = edges.size();
  for (int i = 0; i < size; ++i) {
    Edge* edge = edges.at(i);
    if (edge->node1 == node) {
      cout << "adjacent: " << edge->node2->id << endl;
      adjacentEdges->push_back(edge);
    } else if (edge->node2 == node) {
      cout << "adjacent: " << edge->node1->id << endl;
      adjacentEdges->push_back(edge);
    }
  }
  return adjacentEdges;
}

void RemoveEdge(vector<Edge*>& edges, Edge* edge) {
  vector<Edge*>::iterator it;
  for (it = edges.begin(); it < edges.end(); ++it) {
    if (*it == edge) {
      edges.erase(it);
      return;
    }
  }
}
18/01/2023, 9:54â€¯pm - Syed Abdul Hanan: <Media omitted>
18/01/2023, 10:16â€¯pm - Syed Abdul Hanan: One algorithm that works directly with the prerequisite graph G and computes the minimum number of semesters necessary to complete the curriculum is called "Topological Sort."

The basic idea of the algorithm is to sort the courses based on their dependencies, so that a course can only be taken after all its prerequisites have been completed. The steps of the algorithm are as follows:

Create an empty queue and an empty list to store the result.
For each vertex in G, if it has no incoming edges, add it to the queue.
While the queue is not empty:
a. Remove a vertex from the queue and add it to the result list.
b. For each vertex in G that has an edge going to the vertex that was removed, decrease the incoming edge count by one.
c. If a vertex's incoming edge count is zero, add it to the queue.
Count the number of distinct lists in the result list.
The time complexity of this algorithm is O(n+m) because it uses a single pass to compute the topological ordering of the courses and the graph traversal is linear in the number of edges and vertices of G.
18/01/2023, 10:18â€¯pm - Syed Abdul Hanan: One efficient algorithm that takes as input a directed acyclic graph G = (V, E), and two vertices s and t âˆˆ V, and outputs the number of different directed paths from s to t is called "Path Counting using Dynamic Programming."

The basic idea of the algorithm is to use dynamic programming to count the number of paths from s to t by breaking the problem down into smaller subproblems. The steps of the algorithm are as follows:

Create an array path[n] where n is the number of vertices in G, and initialize all elements to 0.
Set path[s] = 1, as there is 1 path from s to itself.
For each vertex v âˆˆ V in topological order:
a. For each edge (u, v) âˆˆ E:
i. Increment path[v] by path[u].
Return path[t], which represents the number of different directed paths from s to t.
18/01/2023, 10:19â€¯pm - Syed Abdul Hanan: One efficient algorithm to fill in the entire cost array for directed acyclic graphs is called "Bottom-Up Dynamic Programming."

The basic idea of the algorithm is to use dynamic programming to fill in the cost array by starting from the leaf nodes and working towards the root nodes. The steps of the algorithm are as follows:

Create an array cost[n] where n is the number of vertices in G, and initialize all elements to the price of the corresponding vertex.
Perform a topological sort of the vertices in G, which will give a linear ordering of the vertices.
For each vertex u in topological order:
a. For each vertex v such that (u,v) is an edge in G:
i. set cost[u] = min(cost[u], cost[v])
The array cost now contains the cheapest node reachable from each vertex including itself.
The time complexity of this algorithm is O(n+m), where n is the number of vertices and m is the number of edges in G. This is because it requires a topological sort of the vertices which takes O(n+m) time, and a single pass to fill in the cost array which is also linear in the number of vertices and edges.

This algorithm is efficient because it uses dynamic programming to solve the problem by breaking it down into smaller subproblems and reusing the solutions of subproblems to solve the original problem. Since the graph is DAG, the topological sort will give us the correct order of traversing the vertices, and the cost array will be filled correctly.

08/02/2023, 8:51â€¯pm - Syed Abdul Hanan: def get_baseline_scores(est_names, X_train, y_train_val, cv):
    baseline_scores_list = []
    for est_name in est_names:
        pipe = Pipeline(steps=[("scaler", StandardScaler()),
                               ("estimator", globals()[est_name])])
        
        est_res = cross_validate(pipe,
                                 # https://github.com/dmlc/xgboost/issues/6908,
                                 np.ascontiguousarray(X_train),
                                 y_train_val,
                                 cv=cv, return_train_score=True)
        baseline_scores_list.append(
            pd.DataFrame({"estimator": est_name, 
                          "train_score": est_res.get("train_score"),
                          "val_score": est_res.get("test_score"), 
                          "fit_time_s": est_res.get("fit_time")
                         }))
    baseline_scores_df = (pd.concat(baseline_scores_list)
                          .sort_values("val_score", ascending=False))
    return baseline_scores_df


def fmt_bl_scores(scores_df, caption):
    metric_cols = ["train_score", "val_score", "fit_time_s"]
    final_df = (scores_df
                .pipe(pd.pivot_table, 
                      values=metric_cols, 
                      index="estimator", 
                      aggfunc={columns: np.mean for columns in metric_cols})
                .sort_values("val_score", ascending=False)
                
                # display options
                .style.format("{:.1%}", subset=["train_score", "val_score"])
                .set_table_attributes("style='display:inline'")
                .set_caption(caption)._repr_html_())
    return final_df

blc_w_pwr = get_baseline_scores(["log_reg", "rfc", "knc", "lgbc", "svc"],
                                X_train_val_w_pwr, clf_y_train_val, skf)
blc_no_pwr = get_baseline_scores(["log_reg", "rfc", "knc", "lgbc", "svc"],
                                 X_train_val_no_pwr, clf_y_train_val, skf)

blr_w_pwr = get_baseline_scores(["lin_reg", "rfr", "knr", "lgbr", "svr"],
                                X_train_val_w_pwr, reg_y_train_val, kf)
blr_no_pwr = get_baseline_scores(["lin_reg", "rfr", "knr", "lgbr", "svr"],
                                 X_train_val_no_pwr, reg_y_train_val, kf)
        
display_html(
    fmt_bl_scores(blc_w_pwr, 
                  "Baseline classifier accuracy (with power columns)") +
    "\xa0" * 2 +  # so both still fit in a line on small screens
    fmt_bl_scores(blc_no_pwr, 
                  "Baseline classifier accuracy (no power columns)") +
    "<br/><br/>" +
    fmt_bl_scores(blr_w_pwr,
                  "Baseline regressor R2 (with power columns)") +
    "\xa0" * 2 +
    fmt_bl_scores(blr_no_pwr, 
                  "Baseline regressor R2 (no power columns)"),
    raw=True
)

## RF permutation importances (model agnostic method)
rfr.fit(X_train_wp, reg_y_train_wp)
rfr_pi_res = permutation_importance(rfr, X_train_wp, reg_y_train_wp,
                                   n_repeats=10, random_state=0)
rfr_pi_df = (pd.DataFrame(rfr_pi_res.get("importances"),
                         index=X_train_wp.columns,
                         columns=[i + 1 for i in range(10)])
            .reset_index()
            .pipe(pd.melt,
                  id_vars=["index"], value_vars=[i + 1 for i in range(10)],
                  var_name="rep", value_name="permutation_importance")
            .rename(columns={"index": "features"}))
rfr_pi_order = (rfr_pi_df.groupby("features")
               .mean("permutation_importance")
               .sort_values("permutation_importance", ascending=False).index)

## Logistic Regression/Linear SVC coefficients (L1-based)
ss = StandardScaler()
def plot_abs_coefs(model_inst, model_name, y_train, ax):
    coefs_df = pd.DataFrame(
        {"features": X_train_wp.columns,
         "coefficients": (model_inst
                          .fit(ss.fit_transform(X_train_wp), clf_y_train_wp)
                          .coef_.flatten())}
    ).assign(abs_coef = lambda x: x["coefficients"].map(abs))
    feat_order = (coefs_df
                  .groupby("features").mean("abs_coef")
                  .sort_values("abs_coef", ascending=False).index)
    (sns.barplot(data=coefs_df, x="abs_coef", y="features",
                color="lightgrey", order=feat_order, ax=ax)
     .set(title=f"Absolute values of {model_name} coefficients"))
    
## Plots
fig, axs = plt.subplots(2, 2, figsize=(12, 8))
plt.subplots_adjust(wspace=0.3, hspace=0.4)

plot_importance(lgbc, xlabel="Total gains of splits which use the feature", 
                title="LightGBM Classifier feature importance",
                importance_type="gain", precision=0, grid=False, ax=axs[0, 0])
plot_abs_coefs(model_inst=LogisticRegression(solver="liblinear", penalty="l1"),
               model_name="logistic regression", 
               y_train=clf_y_train_wp, ax=axs[0, 1])

sns.barplot(data=rfr_pi_df, x="permutation_importance", y="features",
            ci="sd", order=rfr_pi_order, color="lightgrey",
            ax=axs[1, 0]).set(title="RF Regressor permutation importance")
plot_abs_coefs(model_inst=LinearSVR(random_state=1, max_iter=2000),
               model_name="linear SVR", y_train=reg_y_train_wp, ax=axs[1, 1]);

    cv = skf if pred_task == "clf" else kf
    y_train_val = clf_y_train_val if pred_task == "clf" else reg_y_train_val
    
    pipeline_steps = Pipeline(
        steps=[("transformer", StandardScaler()),
                ("estimator", globals()[estimator_name])]
    )
    
    common_args = dict(estimator=pipeline_steps, n_jobs=-1, 
                       cv=cv, verbose=1,
                       return_train_score=True,  # to check for overfitting
                       error_score="raise")  # if error during fitting
    random_cv = RandomizedSearchCV(param_distributions=search_params, 
                                   n_iter=60, random_state=1, **common_args)
    grid_cv = GridSearchCV(param_grid=search_params, **common_args)
    search_cv = grid_cv if search_mode == "grid" else random_cv

    search_cv.fit(X_train_val, y_train_val)
    return search_cv


def fmt_search_res(search_res):
    summary_df = pd.DataFrame(
        {key: search_res.cv_results_.get(key) 
         for key in ["params", "rank_test_score", 
                     "mean_fit_time", "mean_score_time",
                     "mean_train_score", "mean_test_score",
                     "std_train_score", "std_test_score"]}
    )
    
    final_df = (pd.DataFrame(summary_df["params"].tolist())  # expand params
                .reset_index()
                .merge(summary_df.reset_index(drop=True).reset_index())
                .drop(["index", "params"], axis=1)
                .sort_values(["mean_test_score", "mean_fit_time"], 
                             ascending=[False, True]))
    return final_df


# feature transformations important for distance-based algo eg. SVM, KNN
transformers = [StandardScaler(),  # very sensitive to outliers
                RobustScaler(),  # not affected by a few extreme outliers
                FunctionTransformer(lambda x: x),  # do nothing
                QuantileTransformer()]  # collapses outliers
08/02/2023, 8:54â€¯pm - Syed Abdul Hanan: lgb_params = {
    "transformer": transformers,
    # generally, slower learning rates need more trees
    "estimator__n_estimators": [50, 100, 250, 500],  # default 100
    "estimator__learning_rate": [0.001, 0.01, 0.1, 0.2, 0.3],  # default 0.1
    "estimator__boosting_type": ["gbdt", "dart"],  # default gbdt
    # restrict tree growth and adjust regularisation to prevent overfitting
    "estimator__max_depth": [25, 50, -1],  # default -1 (no limit)
    "estimator__min_child_samples": [20, 30, 40],  # default 20
    "estimator__reg_alpha": np.logspace(-2, 2, 5),  # lambda_l1; default 0
    "estimator__reg_lambda": np.logspace(-2, 2, 5)  # lambda_l2; default 0
}

lgbc_raw_clf_res = gen_search_eval("lgbc", lgb_params, "clf", "random")
print(f"\nBest classifier pipeline: {lgbc_raw_clf_res.best_estimator_}")

lgbc_clf_res = fmt_search_res(lgbc_raw_clf_res)
lgbc_clf_res.head(3)

08/02/2023, 8:54â€¯pm - Syed Abdul Hanan: def get_tuned_score(est_name:str, task:str):
    score = globals()[f"{est_name}_raw_{task}_res"].best_score_
    return score

summary_df_display_text = ""

for bl_df, mode in zip([blc_no_pwr, blr_no_pwr], ["clf", "reg"]):
    caption = "classifier summary" if mode == "clf" else "regressor summary"
    html_text = (
        bl_df
        .pipe(pd.pivot_table,
              values="val_score",
              index="estimator",
              aggfunc=np.mean)
        .rename(columns={"val_score": "baseline"})
        .reset_index()
        .sort_values("baseline", ascending=False)
        .assign(tuned = lambda x: x["estimator"].apply(get_tuned_score, task=mode),
                diff = lambda x: x["tuned"] - x["baseline"])
        
        # display options
        .style.format("{:.1%}", subset = ["baseline", "tuned", "diff"])
        .set_table_attributes("style='display:inline'")
        .set_caption(caption)._repr_html_()
    )
    summary_df_display_text = summary_df_display_text + html_text + "\xa0" * 2
    
display_html(summary_df_display_text, raw=True)

01/03/2023, 9:22â€¯am - Shafi: FAST Islamabad FYP Ideas shared by Faculty for students to choose for fall 2022.
01/03/2023, 9:22â€¯am - Shafi: "Skill Swap Marketplace"

The idea is to create a platform that allows users to exchange their skills with each other. For example, if one user is a web developer and another user is a graphic designer, they can swap their skills and collaborate on a project together. The platform will be designed as a full-stack web application, with a database backend and a user-friendly frontend.

Here are some key features of the platform:

User profiles: Each user will have a profile page that showcases their skills, experience, and projects they have worked on. Users can also indicate which skills they are interested in learning.

Skill exchange: Users can search for other users who have the skills they need, and propose a skill exchange. For example, a user who needs help with website design can offer their web development skills in exchange for help with design.

Project collaboration: Users can create and collaborate on projects with other users who have complementary skills. The platform can include features such as project management tools, file sharing, and real-time collaboration.

Messaging system: Users can communicate with each other through a messaging system built into the platform. This will allow them to discuss the details of the skill exchange or project collaboration.

Payment system: The platform can include a payment system that allows users to pay for services rendered. This can be used for users who offer professional services or want to offer their skills in exchange for monetary compensation.

The platform can be built using popular web development technologies such as React, Node.js, and MongoDB. The project will require a full-stack approach, including designing the database schema, building the backend API, and creating the frontend user interface.

08/05/2023, 1:15â€¯pm - Syed Abdul Hanan: Attentional all final semester students and recent graduates of AUMC:

Ideagist Online Paid Internship Program 2023
 
Ideagist.com is the world's largest incubator of early-stage ideas with a userbase in 193 countries. Ideagist.com has been providing Pakistani students an opportunity to learn skills necessary in the knowledge economy through an active paid internship program.
 
Full-time stipend during the internship will range from 10K to 25K, depending on the performance. These work-from-home internships can lead to a full-time position at Ideagist global or Ideagist Pakistan's team. Duration of the internship is 6 months, that can be extended to up to 12 months.
 Eligibility Criteria:

1. Only students of 6th or 7th semesters are eligible 
2. Fresh graduates (only for video editing and graphic designing)
3. Min. CGPA 3
4. Have stable Internet Connection
5. Access to laptop and Mobile

Their application deadline is May 12, 2023. Please click on the link below and complete the application form carefully.
Here is the link:
 
https://ideagist.com/internship-registration-form-3/

11/06/2023, 2:48â€¯am - Syed Abdul Hanan: Encrypting Images
Like words, images can also be encrypted. You may consider developing a program for remotely connecting users with security aspects like a login option. A transfer system can also be created and secured with powerful algorithms such as AES, DES, and RSA, upon registration. You can also select a desirable method for connecting multiple sources of data transmission, like transferring data using remote networks and servers and encrypting it with keys. This will prevent any users from accessing the data without having the necessary keys for decryption. This project will reflect and validate your understanding of cryptography.

20/07/2023, 4:45â€¯pm - Shafi: Hello

20/07/2023, 4:48â€¯pm - Shafi: I'm sorry to hear that you're experiencing loneliness and emptiness. It's important to remember that feelings of loneliness can arise even when we know we're doing the right thing or making positive changes in our lives. Loneliness is a complex emotion, and it can have various causes, including:

Change and Adjustment: If you've recently made significant changes in your life, such as starting a new job, moving to a different place, or ending a relationship, it's common to feel lonely as you adjust to your new circumstances.
Loss of Connections: Sometimes, when we make changes, we might lose connections with people who were once a significant part of our lives. This loss can create a void and feelings of isolation.

Expectations vs. Reality: If you had certain expectations about how your life would be after making positive changes, and reality doesn't match up to those expectations, it can lead to disappointment and loneliness.
Self-Reflection: Making positive changes can also lead to increased self-reflection, which can make you more aware of your emotions, including loneliness, leading to a stronger feeling of emptiness.

Lack of Support: Even when you know you're doing the right thing, not having enough emotional support during challenging times can exacerbate feelings of loneliness.

Dealing with loneliness and its associated emptiness can be challenging, but there are some strategies you can try to help cope with these feelings:
Reach Out: Don't hesitate to reach out to friends, family, or support groups. Sharing your feelings with someone you trust can be comforting and remind you that you are not alone.

Engage in Activities: Pursue activities or hobbies that interest you. Engaging in things you enjoy can be a great way to meet like-minded individuals and establish new connections.

Practice Self-Compassion: Be kind to yourself and understand that it's normal to experience loneliness, especially during times of change.

Seek Professional Help: If feelings of loneliness persist and start affecting your well-being, consider seeking support from a therapist or counselor who can help you explore and process these emotions.
Mindfulness and Meditation: Engage in mindfulness or meditation practices to help you stay present and reduce anxiety about the past or the future.

Remember that it's okay to feel lonely sometimes, and seeking help or support doesn't mean you're weak. It means you're taking care of your emotional well-being, which is an essential aspect of living a fulfilling life.

01/12/2023, 5:58â€¯pm - Shafi: . YouTube View Bot:

Opening Multiple Chrome Browsers:

The bot is designed to open multiple Chrome browsers simultaneously. The number of browsers is determined by the specified number of threads.
Using Different Proxies:

Each Chrome browser is configured to use a different proxy. This ensures that views are generated with varied IP addresses, adding a level of anonymity.
Viewing a Specific YouTube Video:

The primary function of the bot is to open the specified YouTube video. This action is carried out across multiple browsers concurrently.
Specified Time for Viewing:

The bot stays active for a specified time while viewing the YouTube video. This duration is defined by the requester.
Closing Browsers After Specified Time:

After the designated viewing time, the bot closes the opened Chrome browsers. This process is repeated based on the total number of desired views.
Clicking on Specified Number of Ads:

Additionally, the bot has the capability to click on a specified number of ads associated with the video. This feature is optional and is defined by the requester.
Multithreading:

Multithreading is incorporated into the bot, allowing it to operate concurrently with multiple threads. Each thread corresponds to a unique browser session.
Login to Gmail Accounts:

The bot has the ability to log in to Gmail accounts, potentially enhancing the credibility of the views. The requester can select which Gmail accounts to use.
Subscription Feature:

Instead of a separate subscriber bot, the proposal suggests incorporating a feature in the view bot that allows subscribing to the channel of the video being watched if the user hasn't subscribed already.
Secure Interaction with Twitter:

The bot can navigate to a specific Twitter post, click on the Twitter page URL, and potentially interact with a blog page or embedded video. This ensures secure and controlled actions on external platforms.

06/02/2024, 12:12â€¯am - Shafi: Dear Students 
I hope this email finds you well. I am writing to inform you about an exciting opportunity for our students. As you may know, Air University takes pride in its legacy as the founder of technical olympiads in Pakistan. From 2017 to 2019, we organized Pakistan's largest technical olympiad, showcasing the talents of our students and promoting innovation and excellence in various domains.
This year, we are thrilled to announce Airtech'24, Pakistan's largest technical olympiad, organized by Air University. Airtech'24 will feature over 45 competitions, including Computing, Engineering, E-Gaming, Management, Applied and Social Sciences and more. With a prize pool exceeding 1.6 million PKR and additional incentives, Airtech'24 presents an excellent platform for students to showcase their talents and compete against their peers.
To participate, students can simply register early using the provided Registration Form: https://forms.gle/ze4SuCCXccQXZ6gS9. Early registration ensures their spot in the competitions and gives them access to any early bird benefits.
For more information, students can visit the official Airtech website https://auair.tech/ and review the Rulebook.
To stay updated with the latest news and announcements, students can follow our social media pages:
Facebook: https://www.facebook.com/AirTech2k19?mibextid=ZbWKwL
Instagram: https://www.instagram.com/airtech2024?igsh=MW10ZndoMTk3Y291Yw==
Linkedin: https://www.linkedin.com/posts/airtech2024_airtech-tech-entertainment-activity-7155190641713426432-Grht?utm_source=share&utm_medium=member_android
Additionally, students can join Whatsapp community for daily updates and discussions: https://chat.whatsapp.com/GbXrU6a58hFIVb0r2IPjKA.
As per the instructions of the Vice Chancellor, we are encouraged to promote student participation in these events. Therefore, I kindly request your assistance in circulating this information among the students at your campus.
Thank you for your cooperation and support in promoting Airtech'24. Should you have any questions or require further information, please do not hesitate to contact me.
 
Regards,
Engr. Hafiz Saad Shakeel
